          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Colorado Cracks Down on PFAS",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "koenig-heading",
        "tag": "h3",
        "version": 1,
        "renderVersion": "4.0"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "On June 3, Colorado Gov. Jared Polis (D) signed legislation into law that would ban the use of PFAS chemicals in fracking operations in the state. PFAS, also known as “forever chemicals,” are used in an enormous amount of products and processes, from no-stick pans to firefighting foam. While it’s not as good as a full fracking ban, the move is an important step forward to reducing human exposure to PFAS, which have been ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "linked",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "https://theintercept.com/collections/bad-chemistry/",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " to cancer, thyroid disease, obesity, and ulcerative colitis. Sarah Doll, the national director of Safer States, a coalition that works on chemical and toxic policy, ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "said",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "https://www.ehn.org/pfas-fracking-2657471451.html",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " in a statement: “This law puts Colorado at the forefront of states taking action to stop the flow of toxic PFAS chemicals… We anticipate other states to continue this trend.” While New York, Maryland, and Washington have banned fracking, Colorado is the first state to ban PFAS in fracking while keeping fracking legal.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
